  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a property you still have a mortgage on is the most common scenario in residential real estate. The vast majority of owner-occupiers and investors selling in Brisbane have some level of mortgage debt remaining on the property. The process of selling with a mortgage is well-established and your solicitor will manage it, but understanding how it works gives you a clearer picture of what to expect, and helps you avoid a few avoidable problems.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The basic process: the mortgage is discharged at settlement</h2>
      <p>When you sell a property with an existing mortgage, the mortgage is discharged at settlement using the buyer's purchase funds. The sequence at settlement is: the buyer's funds arrive, your lender takes the amount required to pay out the mortgage in full, and you receive the remaining balance. You do not need to pay off the mortgage separately before or during the campaign. It is handled automatically at settlement as part of the conveyancing process.</p>

      <p>In practice, almost all Queensland property settlements in 2027 are handled electronically through PEXA (Property Exchange Australia), the digital settlement platform. Your solicitor will represent you in the PEXA workspace, your lender's legal representative will attend digitally to receive the payout funds, and the transfer of title to the buyer happens simultaneously. The entire process is coordinated in the settlement workspace, and the lender's interest in the title is removed at the same time ownership passes to the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The payout figure: request it early and understand why it changes</h2>
      <p>Your lender will require a discharge authority, which is the formal instruction from you to discharge the mortgage. Your solicitor lodges this on your behalf, but you should initiate contact with your lender as soon as you have an exchange date confirmed. Lenders require time to process the discharge, and leaving it too late can delay settlement.</p>

      <p>You will also need a payout figure: the exact amount required to discharge the mortgage on the expected settlement date. This figure is not fixed. It changes daily because interest accrues on the outstanding balance every day. The figure your lender quotes you today will be slightly different at settlement three or four weeks from now. The PEXA settlement workspace is designed to handle this adjustment automatically, but you and your solicitor should be aware of this dynamic, particularly if settlement is delayed.</p>

      <p>Request the payout figure from your lender several weeks before settlement. Give yourself enough lead time to deal with any administrative delays or lender processing times. Some lenders, particularly major banks with high transaction volumes, can take several business days to issue a discharge authority confirmation. Factor this into your settlement timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the sale price is less than the payout figure</h2>
      <p>This is the scenario that requires immediate attention if it arises. If your property sells for less than the outstanding mortgage balance, you will have a shortfall at settlement: you owe more than the buyer is paying. You are required to make up the difference from other funds. This is not a situation that resolves itself at settlement. Your solicitor and lender must be informed immediately, and you will need to arrange the shortfall funds before the settlement date.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, where property values have been strong, a shortfall at settlement is uncommon for most owner-occupier properties. It is a more realistic risk for investors who purchased at peak prices with high loan-to-value ratios, or for sellers who have had limited time to build equity. If you have any doubt about whether your property will sell for more than you owe, get a current market appraisal before you list, and speak to your lender about your options.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The discharge fee: a small but real cost</h2>
      <p>Lenders charge a fee to discharge a mortgage. This is separate from your loan's exit fee (if any applies to your specific product) and is the administrative fee for removing the mortgage from the title. Discharge fees vary by lender but are typically in the range of $150 to $400. It is a minor cost in the context of a property sale, but it should be factored into your cost-of-sale calculation alongside commission, VPA, conveyancing fees, and rates adjustments.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Multiple mortgages on the title</h2>
      <p>Some properties have more than one mortgage registered on the title. This is common where the owner has refinanced, taken a second loan, or where there is a line of credit secured against the property. Every registered mortgage must be discharged at settlement. Your solicitor will coordinate this, but it adds complexity and additional discharge fees. Inform your solicitor of all loans secured against the property early in the process so they can manage the multiple discharge requests within the settlement timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Portability: an alternative to full discharge</h2>
      <p>If you are selling to buy another property, you may be able to port your existing mortgage to the new property rather than discharging it entirely. Mortgage portability means your existing loan product, interest rate, and terms transfer to the new security property. Not all loan products are portable, and not all lenders support it, but it can be worth exploring with your lender if you want to retain a favourable rate or avoid break costs on a fixed-rate loan.</p>

      <p>Portability works best when the timing of your sale and purchase aligns cleanly, which is not always possible. Your lender and solicitor will need to coordinate closely if you are porting rather than discharging. If the timing is tight or misaligned, a full discharge and new loan may be simpler in practice even if less financially optimal in theory.</p>

